            "content": "# NATS JetStream Backend Design\n\n**Date:** 2026-04-08\n**Status:** Approved\n**Scope:** Add NATS JetStream as a new backend with feature parity to RabbitMQ and SNS-SQS (excluding autoscaler, handled separately in cross-backend redesign).\n\n## Overview\n\nNATS JetStream backend for shove implementing `Publisher`, `Consumer`, and `TopologyDeclarer` traits. JetStream provides persistent streams with consumer groups, ack/nak, message dedup, and subject-based filtering — a natural fit for shove's semantics.\n\n## Module Structure\n\n```\nsrc/backends/nats/\n├── mod.rs              # Module root, re-exports\n├── client.rs           # NatsClient — connection, shutdown\n├── publisher.rs        # NatsPublisher — implements Publisher trait\n├── consumer.rs         # NatsConsumer — implements Consumer trait (includes routing & header logic)\n├── topology.rs         # NatsTopologyDeclarer — implements TopologyDeclarer\n└── consumer_group.rs   # NatsConsumerGroup — multi-consumer spawning\n```\n\nNo separate router or headers modules — JetStream's API is simple enough that routing (ack/nak/publish-to-DLQ) and header extraction live inline in `consumer.rs`.\n\n## Feature Flag\n\nSingle feature flag in `Cargo.toml`:\n\n```toml\n[features]\nnats = [\"dep:async-nats\"]\n\n[dependencies]\nasync-nats = { version = \"0.39\", optional = true }\n```\n\n## Public API (lib.rs re-exports)\n\n```rust\n#[cfg(feature = \"nats\")]\npub mod nats {\n    pub use crate::backends::nats::{\n        NatsClient, NatsConfig,\n        NatsPublisher, NatsConsumer,\n        NatsTopologyDeclarer,\n        NatsConsumerGroup, NatsConsumerGroupConfig,\n    };\n}\n```\n\n## NatsConfig & NatsClient\n\n### NatsConfig\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsConfig {\n    pub url: String,  // e.g. \"nats://localhost:4222\"\n}\n```\n\n- `Debug` impl redacts credentials in the URL.\n\n### NatsClient\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsClient {\n    client: async_nats::Client,\n    jetstream: async_nats::jetstream::Context,\n    shutdown_token: CancellationToken,\n}\n\nimpl NatsClient {\n    pub async fn connect(config: &NatsConfig) -> Result<Self>;\n    pub async fn connect_with_retry(config: &NatsConfig, max_attempts: u32) -> Result<Self>;\n    pub fn jetstream(&self) -> &async_nats::jetstream::Context;\n    pub fn shutdown_token(&self) -> CancellationToken;\n    pub fn is_connected(&self) -> bool;\n    pub async fn shutdown(&self);\n}\n```\n\n- Connection name: `shove-rs-{pid}` (same convention as RabbitMQ).\n- `connect_with_retry`: exponential backoff, same pattern as `RabbitMqClient::connect_with_retry`.\n- `Clone` is cheap — `async_nats::Client` is internally `Arc`-wrapped.\n- `shutdown()`: cancels token, drains client, waits grace period.\n\n## NatsTopologyDeclarer\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsTopologyDeclarer {\n    client: NatsClient,\n}\n\nimpl TopologyDeclarer for NatsTopologyDeclarer {\n    async fn declare(&self, topology: &QueueTopology) -> Result<()>;\n}\n```\n\n### Standard topic\n\n1. **Main stream** — name: `{queue}`, subject: `{queue}`, retention: `WorkQueue`, storage: `File`, discard: `New`.\n2. **DLQ stream** (if topology has dlq) — name: `{queue}-dlq`, subject: `{queue}-dlq`, same settings.\n\nNo hold queue streams — retry delays handled via `nak_with_delay`.\n\n### Sequenced topic\n\n1. **Main stream** — name: `{queue}`, subjects: `{queue}.shard.0` through `{queue}.shard.{N-1}`.\n2. **DLQ stream** (if configured) — name: `{queue}-dlq`, subject: `{queue}-dlq`.\n\n### Idempotency\n\nUses JetStream's `get_or_create_stream` — safe to call multiple times. If stream exists with matching config, it's a no-op.\n\n### Stream config defaults\n\n- `duplicate_window`: 2 minutes (JetStream default, for `Nats-Msg-Id` dedup).\n- `max_ack_pending`: set at consumer creation time, not stream level.\n\n## NatsPublisher\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsPublisher {\n    client: NatsClient,\n}\n\nimpl NatsPublisher {\n    pub async fn new(client: NatsClient) -> Result<Self>;\n}\n\nimpl Publisher for NatsPublisher {\n    async fn publish<T: Topic>(&self, message: &T::Message) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn publish_with_headers<T: Topic>(&self, message: &T::Message, headers: HashMap<String, String>) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn publish_batch<T: Topic>(&self, messages: &[T::Message]) -> Result<()>;\n}\n```\n\n### Subject routing\n\n- **Standard topic**: publish to subject `{queue}`.\n- **Sequenced topic**: `shard = fnv1a_hash(sequence_key) % routing_shards`, publish to `{queue}.shard.{shard}`.\n\n### Headers on every publish\n\n- `Nats-Msg-Id`: stable UUID (JetStream server-side dedup).\n- `Shove-Retry-Count`: `0` (initial publish).\n- User-provided headers from `publish_with_headers` merged in.\n\n### Publish confirmation\n\nUses JetStream `publish_with_ack` — waits for server persistence confirmation before returning `Ok`.\n\n### Retry on failure\n\n3 attempts with exponential backoff (100ms–2s), same as RabbitMQ publisher.\n\n### Batch\n\nNo native JetStream batch API — iterates and publishes individually. Serializes all messages upfront for fail-fast. Pre-computes shard routing keys for sequenced topics.\n\n## NatsConsumer\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsConsumer {\n    client: NatsClient,\n}\n\nimpl Consumer for NatsConsumer {\n    async fn run<T: Topic>(&self, handler: impl MessageHandler<T>, options: ConsumerOptions) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn run_fifo<T: SequencedTopic>(&self, handler: impl MessageHandler<T>, options: ConsumerOptions) -> Result<()>;\n    async fn run_dlq<T: Topic>(&self, handler: impl MessageHandler<T>) -> Result<()>;\n}\n```\n\n### `run()` — concurrent processing\n\n- Creates a durable pull consumer on the main stream, `max_ack_pending = prefetch_count`.\n- Consumer name: `{queue}-consumer`.\n- Fetches messages in batches, spawns handler tasks concurrently (up to prefetch_count in-flight).\n- Handler timeout: wraps handler in `tokio::time::timeout` if configured.\n- Reconnect loop on transient errors with exponential backoff.\n\n### `run_fifo()` — per-key ordered delivery\n\n- Creates N durable pull consumers, one per shard: `{queue}-shard-{i}`, filtering on subject `{queue}.shard.{i}`.\n- Each consumer: `max_ack_pending = 1` (process one, ack, then next).\n- All N consumers run concurrently as spawned tasks — different keys parallel, same key sequential.\n- Same outcome routing as `run()`.\n\n### `run_dlq()` — dead letter consumer\n\n- Creates a durable pull consumer on `{queue}-dlq` stream.\n- Calls `handler.handle_dead()`, then always acks.\n\n### Outcome routing\n\n| Outcome | Action |\n|---|---|\n| `Ack` | `message.ack()` |\n| `Retry` | Increment `Shove-Retry-Count`. If `>= max_retries`: publish to DLQ stream, then ack. Otherwise: `message.nak_with_delay(hold_queues[min(count, len-1)].delay)` |\n| `Reject` | Publish to DLQ stream with death metadata headers, then `message.ack()` |\n| `Defer` | `message.nak_with_delay(hold_queues[0].delay)`, no counter increment |\n\n### DLQ publish headers\n\nWhen publishing to the DLQ stream on reject or max retries exceeded:\n\n- `Shove-Death-Reason`: `\"rejected\"` or `\"max_retries_exceeded\"`\n- `Shove-Original-Queue`: original queue name\n- `Shove-Death-Count`: `1` (incremented if already present)\n- All original headers preserved.\n\n### Metadata extraction from NATS headers\n\n| NATS Header | Maps to |\n|---|---|\n| `Shove-Retry-Count` | `MessageMetadata.retry_count` |\n| `Nats-Msg-Id` | `MessageMetadata.delivery_id` |\n| JetStream message info redelivered flag | `MessageMetadata.redelivered` |\n| All headers | `MessageMetadata.headers` |\n| `Shove-Death-Reason` | `DeadMessageMetadata.reason` |\n| `Shove-Original-Queue` | `DeadMessageMetadata.original_queue` |\n| `Shove-Death-Count` | `DeadMessageMetadata.death_count` |\n\n## NatsConsumerGroup\n\n```rust\npub struct NatsConsumerGroupConfig {\n    pub prefetch_count: u16,\n    pub min_consumers: u16,\n    pub max_consumers: u16,\n    pub max_retries: u32,\n    pub handler_timeout: Option<Duration>,\n    pub concurrent_processing: bool,\n    pub max_pending_per_key: Option<usize>,\n}\n\npub struct NatsConsumerGroup {\n    client: NatsClient,\n    config: NatsConsumerGroupConfig,\n}\n\nimpl NatsConsumerGroup {\n    pub fn new(client: NatsClient, config: NatsConsumerGroupConfig) -> Self;\n    pub async fn run<T: Topic>(&self, handler: impl MessageHandler<T>, shutdown: CancellationToken) -> Result<()>;\n    pub async fn run_fifo<T: SequencedTopic>(&self, handler: impl MessageHandler<T>, shutdown: CancellationToken) -> Result<()>;\n}\n```\n\n- Spawns `min_consumers` initially, each running its own `NatsConsumer`.\n- Each consumer gets a unique durable name: `{queue}-group-{i}`.\n- JetStream load-balances across pull consumers on the same stream automatically.\n- No autoscaler wired in — consumer group spawns a fixed count, ready to be driven by external scaler from the cross-backend autoscaler redesign.\n\n### Sequenced consumer groups\n\n- Each spawned consumer handles all N shards.\n- JetStream single-active-consumer per durable name prevents two group members from consuming the same shard simultaneously.\n\n## Concept Mapping\n\n| Concept | RabbitMQ | SNS-SQS | NATS JetStream |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Queue | AMQP queue | SQS queue | Stream + durable pull consumer |\n| Retry backoff | Separate hold queues with TTL | `ChangeMessageVisibility` | `nak_with_delay` with hold_queue durations |\n| DLQ | Server-side dead-lettering | SQS redrive policy | Explicit publish to `{queue}-dlq` stream |\n| Sequenced delivery | Consistent-hash exchange + N sub-queues | N FIFO topics + N FIFO queues | Single stream, N subject-filtered consumers |\n| Dedup | `x-message-id` (app-level) | Content-based (SNS FIFO) | `Nats-Msg-Id` (server-enforced) |\n| Exactly-once | AMQP transactions (separate feature) | SNS FIFO dedup window | JetStream dedup — always on, no perf penalty |\n| Consumer groups | Multiple consumers on same queue | Multiple SQS pollers | Multiple pull consumers on same stream |\n| Publish confirm | Publisher confirms channel | SNS API response | `publish_with_ack` |\n| Retry count header | `x-retry-count` | SQS message attribute | `Shove-Retry-Count` |\n\n## Not In Scope\n\n- **Autoscaler / queue stats provider** — being redesigned as a cross-backend abstraction separately.\n- **Management API** — NATS monitoring is handled via NATS server monitoring endpoints; not needed for core backend functionality.\n- **Transactional feature flag** — JetStream dedup is always on with no performance trade-off, so no separate `nats-transactional` feature needed.\n",
